@node Multiline toggle
@section Multiline toggle

@findex consult-extras-toggle-multiline
By default, @code{consult-ripgrep} searches line by line. When you need to find patterns that span multiple lines---such as a function signature followed by a specific body expression---the command @code{consult-extras-toggle-multiline} appends the @samp{--multiline --multiline-dotall} flags to @code{consult-ripgrep-args}. Calling it again removes the flags, restoring single-line behavior.

This is a toggle command: it modifies the global value of @code{consult-ripgrep-args}, so the change persists until toggled back or until Emacs is restarted.

@node Directory-scoped search
@section Directory-scoped search

@findex consult-extras-locate-current
@findex consult-extras-locate-file-current
@findex consult-extras-ripgrep-current
Three commands restrict standard @samp{consult} search commands to the current directory (@code{default-directory}):

@itemize
@item
@code{consult-extras-locate-current} runs @code{consult-locate} scoped to the current directory. On macOS, it uses @samp{mdfind-wrapper} with the @samp{-onlyin} flag to restrict Spotlight's search scope. This is useful when you want to find a file somewhere within the current project tree without searching the entire filesystem.

@item
@code{consult-extras-locate-file-current} works like @code{consult-extras-locate-current} but adds the @samp{-name} flag, so it matches only against file names rather than file contents or metadata. Use this when you know part of the filename but not its exact location within the directory tree.

@item
@code{consult-extras-ripgrep-current} runs @code{consult-ripgrep} in the current directory. This is a convenience wrapper that passes @code{default-directory} as the search root, saving you from having to specify it interactively.
@end itemize

@node Org heading navigation
@section Org heading navigation

@findex consult-extras-org-heading
When working in a large Org file with many folded subtrees and narrowed regions, jumping to a heading with the standard @code{consult-org-heading} can produce unexpected results: narrowed-away headings are invisible, and folded content may not be reachable.

The command @code{consult-extras-org-heading} addresses this by widening the buffer and unfolding all headings (via @code{org-extras-fold-show-all-headings} from @samp{org-extras.el}) before calling @code{consult-org-heading}. After the jump, it recenters the display so the target heading appears near the top of the window.

It accepts the same optional MATCH and SCOPE arguments as @code{consult-org-heading}, so it can be used as a drop-in replacement.

